***Endocrine system: it is combination od diff diff endocrine glands that help in formation and secretion of chemical and produce harmones:
harmones: it is the chemical that act as massenger and carries information:
| Feature                | Description                                                                          |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Main function**      | Controls body activities by releasing hormones into the blood.                       |
| **Type of control**    | Slow but long-lasting (compared to the nervous system which is fast but short-term). |
| **Mode of transport**  | Hormones travel through the **bloodstream** to target organs.                        |
| **Nature of hormones** | Chemical messengers made by glands.                                                  |

  **Major endocrine glands and thier funnction:
| Gland                              | Location            | Hormone(s) Secreted                   | Function                                         |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| **Pituitary gland** (Master gland) | Base of brain       | Growth hormone (GH), TSH, FSH, LH     | Controls other glands, growth, and reproduction  |
| **Hypothalamus**                   | Brain               | Releasing hormones                    | Links nervous system and endocrine system        |
| **Thyroid gland**                  | Neck (below larynx) | Thyroxine (T‚ÇÑ), Triiodothyronine (T‚ÇÉ) | Controls metabolism and growth                   |
| **Parathyroid glands**             | Behind thyroid      | Parathyroid hormone (PTH)             | Regulates calcium levels in blood                |
| **Adrenal glands**                 | On top of kidneys   | Adrenaline, Cortisol                  | Helps body respond to stress (‚Äúfight or flight‚Äù) |
| **Pancreas**                       | Behind stomach      | Insulin, Glucagon                     | Controls blood sugar levels                      |
| **Pineal gland**                   | In brain            | Melatonin                             | Regulates sleep‚Äìwake cycle                       |
| **Thymus**                         | Upper chest         | Thymosin                              | Develops immune system in childhood              |
| **Testes** (in males)              | Scrotum             | Testosterone                          | Controls male traits and sperm production        |
| **Ovaries** (in females)           | Pelvic region       | Estrogen, Progesterone                | Controls female traits and menstrual cycle       |

  **Diff in Endocrine and Exocrine glands:
| Feature   | Endocrine Glands            | Exocrine Glands                   |
| --------- | --------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Ducts     | No ducts (ductless)         | Have ducts                        |
| Secretion | Directly into blood         | Into body surfaces or cavities    |
| Example   | Thyroid, Adrenal, Pituitary | Sweat, Salivary, Sebaceous glands |

** Harmones and there function
| Hormone                     | Gland     | Function                                     |
| --------------------------- | --------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| **Insulin**                 | Pancreas  | Lowers blood sugar                           |
| **Glucagon**                | Pancreas  | Raises blood sugar                           |
| **Adrenaline**              | Adrenal   | Increases heart rate, prepares for emergency |
| **Thyroxine**               | Thyroid   | Controls metabolism                          |
| **Growth Hormone (GH)**     | Pituitary | Controls body growth                         |
| **Oxytocin**                | Pituitary | Causes childbirth contractions, milk release |
| **FSH & LH**                | Pituitary | Control reproductive organs                  |
| **Melatonin**               | Pineal    | Regulates sleep                              |
| **Aldosterone**             | Adrenal   | Maintains salt and water balance             |
| **Testosterone**            | Testes    | Male sex hormone                             |
| **Estrogen & Progesterone** | Ovaries   | Female sex hormones                          |

** desases and there disorder
| Disease                | Cause                         | Effect                             |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| **Diabetes mellitus**  | Lack of insulin               | High blood sugar                   |
| **Goitre**             | Lack of iodine                | Swelling of thyroid gland          |
| **Cretinism**          | Lack of thyroxine in children | Stunted growth, mental retardation |
| **Gigantism**          | Excess growth hormone         | Abnormally tall                    |
| **Dwarfism**           | Less growth hormone           | Abnormally short                   |
| **Addison‚Äôs disease**  | Low adrenal hormone           | Weakness, weight loss              |
| **Cushing‚Äôs syndrome** | High cortisol                 | Obesity, high BP                   |
| **Hyperthyroidism**    | Excess thyroxine              | Weight loss, high metabolism       |
| **Hypothyroidism**     | Low thyroxine                 | Weight gain, slow metabolism       |

  ** 6 important points to remember:
Pituitary gland is called the master gland because it controls other glands.

Insulin is the only hormone that lowers blood glucose level.

Adrenaline is called the emergency hormone.

Thyroxine requires iodine for its production.

Pancreas is both endocrine and exocrine in nature.

Hormones act in very small amounts but have powerful effects.

  **Cordination in plants:
Coordination means the ability of an organism to receive information from its surroundings and respond properly to it.
In plants, there is no nervous system or brain, yet they show coordination through:
Hormones (chemical coordination)
Growth movements (tropic and nastic movements)

**Types of cordination:
| Type                      | Based on                       | Example                                         |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------- |
| **Chemical coordination** | Plant hormones (phytohormones) | Auxin promotes growth                           |
| **Growth movements**      | Tropic and nastic movements    | Bending towards light, closing of Mimosa leaves |

Plant harmoes: they are chemical massenger that control growth development and response to stimmuli:

**Main plant harmones:
| Hormone                    | Function                                                  | Example / Effect                                                |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Auxins**              | Promote cell elongation, root formation, and phototropism | Bending of stem towards light                                   |
| **2. Gibberellins (GA)**   | Promote stem elongation, seed germination, flowering      | ‚ÄúFoolish seedling‚Äù disease in rice caused by excess gibberellin |
| **3. Cytokinins**          | Promote cell division and delay aging (senescence)        | Found in young fruits and seeds                                 |
| **4. Abscisic Acid (ABA)** | Inhibits growth, causes leaf fall and dormancy            | Called **stress hormone**                                       |
| **5. Ethylene**            | Helps in fruit ripening and leaf fall                     | Used to ripen fruits artificially                               |

