A ‚Äì Auxin
G ‚Äì Gibberellin
C ‚Äì Cytokinin
A ‚Äì Abscisic acid
E ‚Äì Ethylene

Movements in plants is of two types:
1)1. Tropic Movements (Directional)

‚Üí Movement towards or away from stimulus.
‚Üí Permanent and growth-related.
  | Type              | Stimulus  | Example                                   |
| ----------------- | --------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| **Phototropism**  | Light     | Stem bends **toward** light               |
| **Geotropism**    | Gravity   | Roots grow **downward**, stems **upward** |
| **Hydrotropism**  | Water     | Roots grow **toward** water               |
| **Thigmotropism** | Touch     | Tendrils coil around support              |
| **Chemotropism**  | Chemicals | Growth of pollen tube towards ovule       |

2)Nastic Movements:
| Type            | Stimulus    | Example                                                    |
| --------------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Thigmonasty** | Touch       | Folding of *Mimosa pudica* (touch-me-not) leaves           |
| **Photonasty**  | Light       | Opening and closing of *Datura* or *Morning glory* flowers |
| **Seismonasty** | Shock       | Sudden closing of leaves after shock                       |
| **Thermonasty** | Temperature | Tulip flowers open with rise in temperature                |

**Electrical cordination in plants:
üåø C. Electrical Coordination in Plants

Some rapid movements (like Mimosa pudica) are due to electrical signals between cells ‚Äî similar to nervous signals but slower and simpler.

  **Diff in tropic and nastic movement:
| Feature   | Tropic Movement                  | Nastic Movement            |
| --------- | -------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Direction | Depends on direction of stimulus | Independent of direction   |
| Nature    | Growth movement                  | Non-growth movement        |
| Example   | Bending of stem towards light    | Folding of *Mimosa* leaves |

